                        <par_12
                            jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                            sling:resourceType="wcm/foundation/components/parsys">
                            <container4
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545825687,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <title
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545825678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-11-30T02:11:17.530-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="kumarvx60"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-03-20T11:07:18.552-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="ChemBeads: chemistry coated in glass"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-11-16T17:01:41.718-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-01T04:36:21.639-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="kumarvx60"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>What do tiny glass beads, a powder mixing machine and solid chemicals have in common?&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Not much. Until a group of AbbVie chemists had an idea that could shorten the screening time for some compounds from weeks to days.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Long before there is a medicine, there is a compound. Or rather, thousands of compounds that must be tested in order to find the special few that could one day become a medicine. It’s a long and resource-heavy testing process to identify these “lead compounds” that could possibly be converted into a new medicine.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>To test these compounds, scientists first have to make them. Unfortunately, finding the conditions necessary to make the desired compounds can often be a bottleneck, in part due to the limited amount of material available and a lack of technologies to screen diverse conditions efficiently and effectively. In other words, it adds a time consuming, resource-heavy step to what is already a painfully slow journey from scientific discovery to potential treatment.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container4>
                            <quote_copy
                                cq:styleIds="[1000000000000]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-11-16T17:03:32.882-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2023-01-25T13:19:42.735-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="fusznx"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/quote"
                                attributionName="Amanda Dombrowski, Ph.D."
                                attributionTitle="Senior Scientist, Discovery Chemistry and Technologies, AbbVie"
                                quote="We realized that if we wanted a better solution, we had to find it ourselves."
                                quoteType="regular"
                                textSize="h0"/>
                            <container
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545825687,1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-11-29T14:23:15.605-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="sharmrx18"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-11-29T14:23:15.605-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="sharmrx18"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <title_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545825678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-11-30T02:11:17.530-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="kumarvx60"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-03-20T11:07:31.621-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="In robots v. solids, solids usually win"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-11-16T17:01:41.718-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-01T04:37:32.926-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="kumarvx60"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>The issue chemists run into is that not all compounds are alike in terms of their physical properties; because of this,&amp;nbsp;robots can handle some better than others.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Like nearly everything these days, artificial intelligence was implemented to improve the screening process. But the robots who expedited the screening do better with liquids, which are uniform. Solids have proved more challenging. While liquids are pretty much homogeneous and easy for robots to read, solid chemicals can be fluffy, crystalline, chunky, etc.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Lucky for the robots, human creativity found an answer. Using glass beads and a dry mixing machine, a group of AbbVie chemists – Noah Tu, Ying Wang and Amanda Dombrowski, all members of AbbVie’s high throughput chemistry (HTC) team – came up with an idea that could help the robots do their work.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>The idea was born from frustration, which can be a powerful motivator, Dombrowski says.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container>
                            <image
                                cq:styleIds="[1402843082832,1402843082812]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-01T04:37:47.005-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="kumarvx60"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-01T04:38:23.261-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="kumarvx60"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                jcr:title="Ying Wang (left), Noah Tu (middle), and Amanda Dombrowski (right), all members of AbbVie’s high throughput chemistry (HTC) team who came up with an idea that could help the robots screen solids faster to help chemists speed up the process from scientific discovery to potential treatment."
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/image/v2/image"
                                alt="members of AbbVie’s high throughput chemistry (HTC) team"
                                altValueFromDAM="false"
                                displayPopupTitle="false"
                                fileReference="/content/dam/abbvie-com2/images/stories/chembeads-improving-artificial-intelligence-through-human-ingenuity/chem_beads_body1.jpg"
                                isDecorative="false"
                                titleValueFromDAM="false"/>
                            <container_copy
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545825687,1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:created="{Date}2022-11-29T14:23:15.605-05:00"
                                jcr:createdBy="sharmrx18"
                                jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-11-29T14:23:15.605-05:00"
                                jcr:lastModifiedBy="sharmrx18"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <separator_copy_copy_
                                    cq:styleIds="[1662756423318]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-11-16T10:43:45.922-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-11-16T10:43:45.922-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/separator/v2/separator"/>
                                <separator
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-01T04:45:02.577-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="kumarvx60"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-01T04:45:02.577-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="kumarvx60"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/separator/v2/separator"/>
                                <text_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-11-16T17:01:41.718-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-01T04:39:04.541-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="kumarvx60"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>“The only way for the robots to handle solids was to dissolve the compound into a liquid, which took a lot of work and many times could complicate the reaction screen process,” she says. “So there was really no way to dispense solid compounds easily. We realized that if we wanted a better solution, we had to find it ourselves.”&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>After a few false starts, the team was inspired by a process where medicines are mixed with other inert materials to improve their solid characteristics. They found that glass beads can be coated with solid chemicals by combining them in a dry mixer. Solid chemicals are often very different from each other in terms of physical characteristics, but the chemical coated beads have very similar features, which makes a robot’s job much easier.&lt;br>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;br>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;b>Watch Noah Tu, M.S., senior scientist, discovery chemistry and technologies, AbbVie demonstrate the process:&lt;/b>&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container_copy>
                            <video
