                                <title
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678,1651545825694]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-01T04:41:44.907-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="kumarvx60"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2024-03-20T11:07:41.847-04:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="VALENSX5"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    jcr:title="Making a good idea better, a millionth of a gram at a time"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/title/v2/title"
                                    type="h2"
                                    variant="h"/>
                                <text_copy
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-11-16T17:01:41.718-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-01T04:42:13.915-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="kumarvx60"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>One ChemBead weighs one millionth of a gram, five percent of which is the active chemical, with the remaining 95 percent consisting of the glass bead.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Using automation to dispense these chemically coated glass beads – a process dubbed “ChemBeads” by the chemists who invented it - accelerates and simplifies the process of finding conditions to make a compound. Because of this, these tiny beads are getting a lot of attention.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>“Good science is all about coming up with a good idea and making it better,” Noah Tu, M.S., senior scientist, discovery chemistry and technologies, AbbVie says. “That’s exactly what we did. We came up with the idea of ChemBeads in 2016 and we’ve been refining and improving the technology ever since.”&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Word of ChemBeads spread fast within AbbVie’s chemistry labs, says Anil Vasudevan, Ph.D., senior director, discovery, who over sees the team that includes Tu, Wang and Dombrowski.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>“A few years ago, no one had ever heard of ChemBeads, and today&amp;nbsp;it’s a common phrase in our labs,” Vasudevan says. “When this team first told me about ChemBeads, I thought it would have limited applicability. But they believed in this idea and never gave up. I’m inspired by their determination to find a practical solution to a problem that has plagued drug discovery scientists for a long time.”&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
                            </container_copy_copy>
                            <image_copy
                                cq:styleIds="[1402843082832,1402843082812]"
